I used to think NTFS Inheritance was magic. Now I know it’s just logic. 🧠📂

If you’re new to IT Help Desk or SysAdmin work, file permissions can feel like a black box. You click “Apply,” and 
suddenly access changes everywhere… or nowhere. And sometimes, it breaks things in ways that make no sense.

I recently dove deep into NTFS Inheritance, and here is the plain-English summary of what actually clicked for me:

1️⃣ It’s Like a Family Tree (But for Files)
Permissions don’t just sit on one folder. They flow down from parent to child. 
If you give your boss access to the “Finance” folder, they automatically get access to “Finance/2024” and “Finance/2024/Q1.” 
That’s inheritance. It saves us from having to set permissions on every single subfolder manually.

2️⃣ “Break Inheritance” is a Big Deal
There’s a button called “Disable inheritance.” When you click it, 
you’re essentially saying, “This folder is now an orphan. It no longer listens to its parents.”
⚠️ Lesson Learned: Only break inheritance if you really need unique permissions for that specific folder. 
Otherwise, you create a management nightmare where you have to track permissions individually forever.

3️⃣ Explicit > Inherited
If you manually add a user to a subfolder (explicit permission), that rule wins over whatever the parent folder says 
(inherited permission). This is why sometimes a user has access to a subfolder even if they don’t have access to 
the main folder. It’s not a bug; it’s a feature.

4️⃣ The “Effective Access” Tab is Your Best Friend
Stop guessing. Windows has a built-in tool called “Effective Access” (in Advanced Security Settings). You plug in a 
user name, and it tells you exactly what they can do. It accounts for all the inherited groups, nested groups, and
explicit rules. Use it before you panic.

Why does this matter for Help Desk?
Because 80% of “I can’t open this file” tickets are actually permission inheritance issues. Understanding this saves 
you hours of troubleshooting and prevents you from accidentally giving everyone Full Control just to make the 
error go away.
